#X text 65 36 In the oscillators section the [moog~] object was presented to show how it can go into self-pscillation mode. The [bob~] object can also go into self-oscillation mode with a resonance parameter above "4" \, but since it has no internal noise generator we need to feed it some tiny signal. Here we have white noise divided by 1 million! This is a 120dB drop!, f 62;
#X obj 656 454 out~;
#X obj 738 245 knob 83 110 1760 1 440 empty empty #dfdfdf #7c7c7c #000000 1 0 0 0 1 320 0 0 110 empty empty 0 12 0 -15 0 1 0 0 0 0;
#X floatatom 738 340 8 0 0 0 - - - 12;
#X obj 656 323 impseq~;
#X obj 656 286 bng 21 250 50 0 empty empty empty 0 -10 0 12 #dfdfdf #000000 #000000;
#X obj 656 416 drive~ 10;
#X obj 656 372 resonant~ 0 1e+12, f 24;
#X text 603 261 excite the filter, f 10;
#X text 581 68 Other objects in Pd Vanilla or ELSE are not well suited for self-oscillation as they are more like pure digital filters (no analog emulation whatsoever). But we can go out of our way to force it. Below we have [resonant~] with an impulse as the excitation \, a stupidly high resonant parameter and even an overdrive at the output. Don't take this too seriously \, it's more a didactical example than anything else., f 40;
#X connect 1 0 3 0;
#X connect 1 0 10 0;
#X connect 3 0 4 0;
#X connect 4 0 5 1;
#X connect 5 0 2 0;
#X connect 6 0 5 2;
#X connect 10 0 11 0;
#X connect 11 0 17 1;
#X connect 14 0 15 0;
#X connect 15 0 17 0;
#X connect 16 0 17 2;
#X connect 17 0 9 0;
#X connect 20 0 21 0;
#X connect 21 0 25 1;
#X connect 22 0 25 0;
#X connect 23 0 22 0;
#X connect 24 0 19 0;
#X connect 25 0 24 0;
